  "prompt": "What is the lowest temperature to leave a thermostat so that the pipes don't freeze?",
  "response": "To prevent pipes from freezing, it\u2019s generally recommended to set your thermostat to at least **55\u00b0F (13\u00b0C)** when you\u2019re away from home or during cold weather. This temperature provides a safe buffer to keep the interior of your home warm enough to prevent freezing in most cases.\n\nHowever, the exact temperature can vary depending on factors such as:\n- **Insulation quality:** Poorly insulated homes may require a slightly higher setting.\n- **Exterior pipe exposure:** If pipes are in uninsulated areas like basements, crawl spaces, or exterior walls, you may need additional precautions (e.g., pipe insulation or heat tape).\n- **Local climate:** Extremely cold climates may require a higher thermostat setting or other protective measures.\n\nIf you\u2019re concerned, consider also insulating exposed pipes and keeping cabinet doors open to allow warm air to circulate around plumbing.",
